-- S.Korean shares rally to 3-wk high on dovish Fed outlook, won firmer
-- By Joonhee Yu
-- Wed Oct 29, 2014 02:20AM EDT
-- None



SEOUL, Oct 29 (Reuters) - South Korean shares rallied to a fresh 3-week high on Wednesday, buoyed by expectations that the U.S Federal Reserve will take a dovish stance regarding the timing of its next interest rate hike.

The Korea Composite Stock Price Index (KOSPI) <.KS11> soared 1.84 percent to close at 1,961.17 points, it's highest since October 8. Shares in LG Electronics <066570.KS> surged 4.3 percent after announcing its third-quarter earnings guidance during afternoon trade, which showed July-September profits had more than doubled compared to a year before.[ID:nL3N0SH1B9] Samsung Heavy Industries <010140.KS> shares jumped 7.1 percent after a 288 billion won ($275.07 million) share buyback plan, disclosed via regulatory filing.  The South Korean won <KRW=> was slightly firmer, as dollar bulls were reined in by expectations of the Fed reassuring the market that interest rates could be maintained at near zero levels for a considerable time.